## Migration Analysis

### APIs that break on .NET 8

| API | Location | Problem | Pattern |
|-----|----------|---------|---------|
| `Thread.Interrupt()` | `Stop()` | Obsolete (`SYSLIB0046` in .NET 9), unreliable | Blocking call interruption |
| `Thread.Abort()` | `Stop()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` | Cancellable work loop |
| `ManualResetEvent.WaitOne()` | `RunLoop()` | Not cancellation-aware â€” can't be woken by a token | Blocking call interruption |

### Pre-existing bug (worth fixing during migration)

The original code has a **race condition**: if `Enqueue` is called twice before `RunLoop` wakes, the event is already set on the second call (no-op). After one `Reset` + `Dequeue`, the second item is **stuck in the queue forever**. The migrated version fixes this.

---

### Migrated Code (direct, minimal change)

```csharp
public class EventProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private readonly ManualResetEvent _newEvent = new ManualResetEvent(false);
    private readonly Queue<string> _queue = new Queue<string>();
    private Thread? _thread;
    private readonly object _lock = new object();
    private readonly CancellationTokenSource _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();

    public void Start()
    {
        _thread = new Thread(RunLoop);
        _thread.Start();
    }

    private void RunLoop()
    {
        var handles = new WaitHandle[] { _newEvent, _cts.Token.WaitHandle };

        while (!_cts.Token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            // WaitAny returns the index of the handle that was signaled.
            // Index 0 = new event arrived, Index 1 = cancellation requested.
            int signaled = WaitHandle.WaitAny(handles);
            if (signaled == 1)
                break;

            _newEvent.Reset();

            // Drain all queued items to fix the original race condition
            // where multiple Enqueue calls could occur before one WaitOne.
            while (true)
            {
                string? item;
                lock (_lock)
                {
                    if (_queue.Count == 0)
                        break;
                    item = _queue.Dequeue();
                }
                Handle(item);
            }
        }
    }

    public void Enqueue(string item)
    {
        lock (_lock) { _queue.Enqueue(item); }
        _newEvent.Set();
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        _cts.Cancel();          // signals the token â†’ WaitAny returns immediately
        _thread?.Join(5000);    // wait for graceful exit
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts.Dispose();
        _newEvent.Dispose();
    }

    private void Handle(string item) { /* ... */ }
}
```

### Key changes explained

| Before (.NET Framework) | After (.NET 8) | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `while (true)` | `while (!_cts.Token.IsCancellationRequested)` | Cooperative cancellation â€” loop checks the token |
| `_newEvent.WaitOne()` | `WaitHandle.WaitAny(new[] { _newEvent, _cts.Token.WaitHandle })` | Unblocks on **either** a new item or cancellation |
| `_thread.Interrupt()` | `_cts.Cancel()` | Cancelling the token wakes `WaitAny` immediately |
| `_thread.Abort()` | *(removed)* | Not needed â€” the loop exits cooperatively |
| Single `Dequeue` per wake | Drain loop | Fixes the lost-item race condition |

---

### Idiomatic .NET 8 version (recommended)

If you can refactor further, `Channel<T>` replaces the manual queue + event + lock entirely:

```csharp
public class EventProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private readonly Channel<string> _channel = Channel.CreateUnbounded<string>();
    private readonly CancellationTokenSource _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
    private Task? _task;

    public void Start()
    {
        _task = Task.Run(() => RunLoopAsync(_cts.Token));
    }

    private async Task RunLoopAsync(CancellationToken token)
    {
        try
        {
            await foreach (var item in _channel.Reader.ReadAllAsync(token))
            {
                Handle(item);
            }
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) { }
    }

    public void Enqueue(string item)
    {
        _channel.Writer.TryWrite(item);
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        _channel.Writer.Complete();  // signal no more items
        _cts.Cancel();               // interrupt if blocked waiting
        _task?.Wait(5000);
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts.Dispose();
    }

    private void Handle(string item) { /* ... */ }
}
```

---

### Pitfalls to watch for

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---|---|
| **`Thread.Abort` â†’ `PlatformNotSupportedException`** | This is a hard crash, not a warning. There's no workaround â€” you must remove it. |
| **Cancellation isn't immediate** | Unlike `Abort`, the token only takes effect at the next checkpoint (`WaitAny`, `ThrowIfCancellationRequested`, `ReadAllAsync`). If `Handle()` is long-running, pass the token into it too. |
| **Dispose `CancellationTokenSource`** | It's `IDisposable` â€” leaking it leaks timers and callbacks. Always wrap with `using` or explicit `Dispose()`. |
| **Don't catch and swallow `OperationCanceledException`** | Catch it only at the top-level loop to exit gracefully. Don't suppress it mid-chain. |
| **`Thread.Interrupt` is also obsolete** | Even though it still *works* on .NET 8, it's marked `SYSLIB0046` starting .NET 9. Migrate it now. |
